
			ENHANCED ROM FOR MODEL 4/4D

Congratulations on purchasing the "X" or "XD" ROM for the Model 4/4D.
These products have been developed over several years and provide numerous
enhancements to the capabilities and performance of your machine.

Important:	Read the license and warranty terms before opening the
		ROM package.  If you have obtained the wrong product or
		you cannot agree to the license and warranty terms, return
		the entire package with the ROM package still sealed for a
		full refund.  The product must be returned within 30 days.
		Once the ROM package is opened, only exchanges for identical
		parts will be made.


Please read over the instructions carefully before using your part.  They
will warn you of things to watch for during the disassembly and reassembly
of your computer, and will also tell you how to take advantage of functions
that were not available before.


Some of the features that the "X" ROM provides include:

	o	Ability to boot LS-DOS 6.3 or TRSDOS 6.2 directly from
		a hard disk drive without using a startup diskette.
		(You must use the HBUILD6 utility to install a new
		 boot track on your LS-DOS 6.3 or TRSDOS 6.2 hard disk.
		 The ability to boot LDOS 5.3 in a similar fashion
		 is under development at this time.)

	o	When running in Model III mode, the ROM driver 
		allows the keyboard to produce all 128 ASCII
		character codes.   The keyboard repeat rate and other
		parameters can also be adjusted.

	o	If your system has Network III or Network 4 hardware,
		either can be booted by pressing a single key.

	o	When running in Model III mode at 4MHZ, the real-time
		clock continues to keep correct time and the cursor
		blink remains constant.


How It Works

The Model III, 4 and 4D contain three code ROM's.  These allow the machine
to provide BASIC when the machine does not have a disk drive.  When running
a Model III disk operating system (LDOS, NEWDOS, TRSDOS 1.x, etc), the
ROM continues to provide many needed services to both the DOS and to
programs that you run.  In addition, Disk BASIC only adds functions
to the existing ROM BASIC.

The code in the Model 4 and 4D version of these ROMs varies slightly from
what was in the Model III.  (These changes deal with initializing the
Model 4/4D hardware and supporting the extra keys on the keyboard.)

The three ROMs are named the "A", "B" and "C" ROMs.  The "A" ROM contains
8192 bytes of code that consist of machine independent operations and some
of BASIC.   The "B" ROM is 4096 bytes long and contains the rest of ROM
BASIC.  The "C" ROM is 2048 bytes long and contains code that controls
functions that change depending on where the machine is to be sold.
For instance, if the Model 4 has a German keyboard, the keyboard driver has
to be different.  The keyboard driver is in the "C" ROM, so only a single
code ROM has to be replaced.

The Model 4D really only has two physical ROMs.  Two 8192 byte ROMs are used.
The first ROM is called the "A" ROM and is identical to the one "A" ROM used
in the Model 4.  The second ROM is called the "D" ROM.  It contains the
code that was in both the "B" and "C" ROMs in a Model 4.  An additional
2K of code in the "D" ROM is only used during the manfuacturing burn-in
process and cannot normally be accessed.

The "X" or "XD" ROM you have purchased replaces the "C" ROM used in the
Model 4, or the "D" ROM used in the Model 4D.


What you should know before starting the installation

Installing the "X" or "XD" ROM requires that you disassemble your computer.
When you do this, the "warranty seal" will be broken.  The strictest reading
of the Radio Shack repair policy is that any remaining warranty (original
or a repair warranty) will be void if the seal is broken, and if the machine
is ever repaired again by Radio Shack, the technicians may remove or replace
any "alien" components to restore the unit to its original state.

However, in 1982 Ed Juge (the Press Officer of Radio Shack/Tandy)
clarified how "alien" modifications are handled by
Radio Shack Service Centers.  In "TRS-80 Microcomputer News", July/August
1982, and in "80-US", May 1982, Mr. Juge states that Radio Shack will
service a machine with a modification and will ignore it if doesn't seem
to be hurting anything.  If the modification prevents the technician
from properly testing the unit, they may ask you for permission to remove
it. 

It is also possible
that some future repair may require the CPU board be exchanged and the
technician may not notice that you have a different ROM in your
machine and may fail to move the "X" or "XD" ROM to the replacement
board.  To avoid this, be sure to tell the technician that you have a
special ROM in the "C" (Model 4) or "D" (Model 4D) position.  Be sure this
gets written down on the repair ticket in case a different person ends up
working on your machine.   You should leave the sticker on your "X" or "XD"
ROM, as this will help identify it as a special part.

You should also keep your old "C" or "D" part so that you can either replace
it in your Model 4 or 4D before taking your machine in for repair, or have
it available if the technician wants to use it in place of the "X" or "XD"
part while repairing the machine.

This information is not meant to alarm you.  It just advises you of
things you should be aware of if your machine ever requires service in
the future.   Since the "X" or "XD" ROM is compatible with the old
"C" and "D" ROM, the tests the technician might run will produce identical
results.   As a rule, the repair centers are very cooperative.


Installation

As discussed above, installing the "X" or "XD" ROM requires your computer
to be disassembled.  The entire job can be done in about 20 minutes.  Two
steps are much easier if you have a second person to help.  Read the
following steps and if the procedure seems beyond your capabilities, seek
help from a local computer store, TV repair store or local college.

The installation instructions are written for the person who has never
disassembled a Model 4 or 4D before, but are able to perform repairs
on the car or the toaster.   If you have installed a battery-powered
clock in your machine or changed a disk drive, the instructions need
only be skimmed.  Otherwise, read each step entirely and then perform
the action.  It is suggested that you place a check mark next to
each step as it is completed so that you won't skip anything.


The following procedure applies to the Model 4.  If you have a Model 4D,
skip down to the procedure for that machine.  If you are uncertain of what
type of Model 4/4D you have, look at the back of the machine.  If there is a
RS-232 connector (a 25 pin connector) sticking out of the back of the machine,
it is a Model 4D.  This connector is on the bottom on a Model 4.  (Do not
look at the bottom of the machine for this check, as both machine have several
connectors there.)


Installaing the "X" ROM in the Model 4   (no connector on the back)

1.	You will need a medium-sized Phillips screwdriver, a small
	flat-blade screwdriver (1/4" wide tip or smaller), a large
	towel (or towels) that will cover a 5' x 3' area, and a
	table or workbench with at least 5' x 3' of space.

2.	Place the cloth or towel over the area that is to be used.
	This will protect the surface of the table and the case of
	computer during disassembly.

3.	Disconnect any cables leading to the Model 4 including the
	power cord.

4.	Place the Model 4 on the left hand side of the table
	and lay it on its left side, as one looks at the keyboard.

5.	Remove the ten Phillips screws that hold the top and bottom
	of the case together.   Keep track of where the screws come from as
	they may be of different types and sizes.  In some cases, one or more
	screws may be missing or may be hidden under the warranty seal.  Two
	recessed screws on either side of the case are sometimes hard to
	remove.  If you don't have a magnetized screwdriver, simply unscrew
	them until they are loose.  They should fall out in the next step.

6.	Set the machine upright by tipping it from its side.  It
	should now be on the right side of the table.  While lifting
	the machine, keep in mind that the cover is loose, so hold the
	top and bottom sections together.
	If you had trouble with the two side screws, check to see that
	they have fallen out onto the table.  If they did not, go back
	to Step 4.

7.	Remove the Phillips screw from the back of the cabinet.  It is
	possible that this part was left out after some previous
	disassembly.

8.	Close the latches on both floppy drives.

9.	READ STEP 9 ENTIRELY BEFORE DOING STEP 9.

	Very carefully, lift the top half of the case STRAIGHT UP.
	Watch the neck of the CRT through the vent at the top of the
	computer, or through the top floppy drive hole.  It is VERY
	IMPORTANT that you not lift the cover at an angle or push the
	cover towards the back because the CRT socket or cabling could
	catch on the lower half of the chassis and break the tube.  If you
	have a second person to help, have them watch the CRT neck and
	give directions as you lift.  Do not allow the top half of
	the computer to slip or drop, as the CRT could implode.

	Once the top is clear of the lower half of the computer, lay
	the top on its side next to the bottom half.  The cables from
	the bottom half to the top half are long enough to do this.
	The top half should be on the left side of the computer now, as
	one looks at the keyboard.

10.	Move around to the back of the computer.  If a metal plate covers
	the circuit boards (across the back), remove the brass-colored screws
	that hold the cover in place.  These are located across the top
	and sides of the CPU enclosure.  Do not remove the screws that
	hold the CPU to the plastic base.  If there is no shield, skip
	to step 13.


11.	Some machines are equipped with Network 4 or a Model III graphics
	hardware.  These boards (only one can be present in a machine)
	are mounted on the shield.  If these boards are present, one or
	more multi-wire cables will plug into connectors that stick
	out of a slot in the shield.  Make a note of where each connector
	goes (label them if necessary) and unplug them from the connector(s)
	on the shield.

12.	Once the screws are removed, gently fold the shield (metal surface
	that faces the back of the machine) down.  In some production
	runs, there are small metal hooks to hold the cover in place while the
	screws are being inserted.  By bending the cover back in one area at a
	time, the cover should fold down so that the CPU board is revealed.

	Some units also have a metal foil across the bottom of the shield.
	If this prevents the shield from folding down, peel it off the
	shield but leave it attached to the base of the machine.  You will
	have to re-apply the foil later, so don't destroy it.

	
13.	You should now be able to see the CPU board.  At the bottom of
	the circuit board, just to the left of center are the three ROMs used
	in the Model 4.  These are 24 pin parts.  Near each socket (usually
	just above it) is written a number like U70.  U70 is where the CROM
	is located and this is the part we will change.   

	If you cannot find U70, or the socket with that number is the wrong
	size, don't panic.   There were several different circuit boards
	built for the Model 4, and the one you have may have the socket
	in a slightly different place or it may have a different
	socket number.

	Search the CPU board for the following items and you should be
	able to identify the "C" ROM:

		1.	The chip must have 24 pins.

		2.	There should be two other 24 pin chips adjacent
			(in the same row) to the chip you located.

		3.	The part number on the chip ends in "16".  For
			example, MCM68A316, 8042316, 2716, 2516, etc.

	Once you locate a chip that meets these requirements, you have
	located the correct part.  The "A" and "B" ROMs have part
	numbers that end in "64" and "32", so it should be pretty easy
	to identify the "C" ROM.   


		There is another 24 pin part that has been mistaken for
		the CROM because it has a number stamped on it that
		ends in "16".  It usually also has the part number 8049007
		and is not located near any other 24 pin parts.  This part
		is NOT the CROM.   Be sure that all three "rules" listed
		above are met.


14.	On one end of the ROM there will be a notch, indention or small
	"divot".  This indicates which end of the ROM has pin 1.  It is
	extremely important to remember which way the ROM goes in so that
	the new ROM can be installed correctly.   Although the CPU board
	may also have a "1" marked on it indicating where pin 1 is, CPU
	boards have been known to be incorrectly marked.  

15.	Remove the "C" ROM from the socket.  If you know how remove the ROM,
	skip to 16.   

	If you don't know how to remove the IC, here is one way to do it
	with the tools you have.   Using the blade of the flat-blade 
	screwdriver, slip the end between the IC and the socket on either
	end of the chip.  DO NOT try to do this between the pins.  Insert the
	screwdriver only a quarter of an inch, or less.  Now rotate the
	screwdriver VERY GENTLY so that the chip lifts away from the socket.
	If you can't so this, then use the screwdriver as a lever and pry
	the chip up NO MORE than 1/8 of an inch.  DO NOT try to pry the chip
	out of its socket with a single motion or you could bend or break
	the pins, or even crack the chip.

	Now that you have one end of the chip lifted slightly, insert
	the screwdriver further under the chip (about 3/4 of an inch, or
	as far as it will go without forcing), and repeat the process.
	This will lift the chip out of its socket without bending the pins.
	You may have to insert the screwdriver one more time to completely
	lift the chip.

	If the chip has not fallen out, you should be able to grasp it on
	each end with a finger and pull it straight out.  If it is too tight
	to be removed using two fingers, repeat the screwdriver maneuver.

16.	If you don't have the package the "X" ROM came in at your table,
	get it.  Remove the "X" ROM from the foam or tube.  If the chip
	was packaged in foam, check between the pins for any small pieces
	of the foam that may have stuck to the pins or to the chip.
	Remove these particles.

17.	Insert the old "C" ROM pins into the foam or the tube.  This will
	protect the part from static electricity.

18.	Insert the "X" ROM into the socket the "C" ROM came from.  Make
	sure the notch, indention or "divot" on the chip is facing the
	same way as the "C" ROM.   This is most important, as 
	improper insertion will ruin the ROM and void the warranty.

	Line the chip up so that its legs are sitting in the sockets.
	You may have to bend one or more pins ever so slightly to get them
	all started into the socket.   When everything appears to be
	lined up, press the chip into the socket part-way by pressing it
	with your thumb.  Confirm that all the pins are still going into
	the socket and that none are going outside the socket or are
	bending under the chip.  (The top of the pin usually bows out
	if the bottom of the pin is bending under the chip.)
	If one or more pins are out of line, remove chip using the
	screwdriver method, and straighten the pins out that are not
	inserting properly.  Then try again.  It may take a few tries
	to get all the pins going into the socket.

	If the pins are still going into the socket after you have pushed
	it halfway into place, push it down until it feels firmly seated.
	There is usually about 1/8 to 1/16 of an inch between the bottom
	of the chip and the socket when it is inserted properly.

	Do not try to force the chip flush with the socket.  Some sockets
	are designed to prevent you from doing this and the excessive
	force could crack the CPU board.

	Now run your finger along the pins on either side.  If one feels like
	it is out of line, examine it carefully, as it may have folded under
	the chip despite your efforts.  If you have a flashlight, examine
	the pins by looking under the chip from one end.  If a leg is bent,
	carefully remove the chip, straighten the leg very slowly and try
	again.  A IC leg can usually be straightened twice without breaking, 
	but that is all.

19.	In the upper half of the case, check the connector that attaches
	to the video board (mounted on the side of the cover).  Sometimes
	this comes loose when the machine is disassembled.  Make sure
	the connector is pushed all the way onto the circuit board.  

20.	Re-install the shield over the CPU board if your machine had one.
	If there was a piece of foil-covered tape along the bottom of the
	shield, be sure the foil is on the outside of the shield when
	you put it back in place.   Press the tape into place and if the
	adhesive is not holding the tape in place, use non-fiber packing
	tape or electricians tape to hold it in position.

	Once the shield is back in position, insert and tighten the
	screws that hold the shield in place.

	If your machine has the Network 4 or Model III graphics boards,
	reconnect the cables that you removed earlier.   If you have
	the Model III graphics board and fail to reconnect these cables
	correctly, the screen will not display anything when you test the
	installation.

21.	At this point, you can either completely reassemble the machine,
	or test the ROM first.   If you want to go ahead and reassemble
	the machine, Skip to step 24.



Testing the "X" ROM installation with the machine disassembled

	CAUTION!	HIGH VOLTAGE EXISTS WITHIN THE CABINET WHEN
			POWER IS APPLIED, EVEN WHEN THE POWER SWITCH
			IS OFF.  AVOID TOUCHING ANY METAL SURFACES.
			NEVER TOUCH ANY OF THE CIRCUITS WHILE POWER
			IS APPLIED TO THE COMPUTER.

22.	Reach under the right edge of the machine and turn the power switch
	on.  Because the 120 volt connections to that switch are exposed
	while the cover is removed, that area should be avoided during
	this test.   For this test, the computer will be turned on and
	off by plugging it into the wall or an extension cord.

23.	Plug the power cable into the wall.  The floppy drive should light
	and the motor should run for a few seconds and then stop.  Wait a
	minute for the CRT to warm up. If no picture appears, adjust the
	brightness and contrast controls on the left side of the base, but
	AVOID TOUCHING ANY WIRES.   Turn both controls to maximum so that
	you can see the screen raster.

	If the drive light did not come on, press RESET.
	If it still does not light, and/or the screen shows random
	characters, something is wrong with the machine.  The ROM may
	be improperly installed or a cable could have been knocked loose
	inside the machine.  The shield could also be shorting something
	out, or the ROM is defective.  Disconnect the power and wait one
	minute.  Then remove the shield and make sure it was not cutting
	into any wires and the foil tape was not under the shield. 

	Once disassembled, if nothing obvious presents itself, replace
	the "X" ROM with the original "C" ROM and see if the machine
	works correctly.   If so, the "X" ROM you have may be defective
	and it should be returned for replacement.   


	If the drive light came on for a few seconds and went back off,
	the message "Diskette" should be on the display.  If there is
	no text on the screen, adjust the brightness and contrast controls.
	If you still don't see the message, press RESET.  If the screen
	still is blank, then one of the video connectors probably has
	come loose.  One is located on the video board and the other end
	plugs into the CPU board near the upper right corner as you look
	at the CPU.  Unplug the power and wait one minute before touching
	these connectors.

	If the message "Diskette" appears, press <BREAK>  The "Cass?"
	prompt should appear.  Press <ENTER> and wait for "Ready".
	Now press <CTRL>; and you should see ^. Pressing <CTRL>- should
	display the underline (_).   This indicates the ROM was installed
	correctly.

	Unplug the power cord and proceed to reassemble the computer.


Reassemble the Computer

24.	Make sure the power cord is unplugged.    From the front of the
	machine, lift the cover and place it over the computer base.
	Watch the neck of CRT through the top vents or through the
	top floppy drive opening in the cover.  The cover should be guided
	so that the CRT neck does not strike the CPU enclosure and does
	not hang on any of the wires that are routed near the CRT.
	If the CRT socket won't clear the wires, remove the cover and
	adjust the wiring so that the CRT and its socket have more room.
	If you have a second person to help, they should assist in guiding
	the cover into position.

25.	Now, plug in your computer and turn the power switch on.
	The light on floppy drive 0 should come on at once and go off
	after about three seconds.  It is does not, press RESET.
	If it still does not light, and/or the screen shows random
	characters, something is wrong with the machine.  The ROM may
	be improperly installed or a cable could have been knocked loose
	inside the machine.  The shield could also be shorting something
	out, or the ROM is defective.  Disconnect the power and disassemble
	the machine and check for problems like the shield cutting into
	a wire, pins on the ROM not in the inserted into the socket,
	ROM inserted upside down, etc.

	Once disassembled, if nothing obvious presents itself, replace
	the "X" ROM with the original "C" ROM and see if the machine
	works correctly.   If so, the "X" ROM you have may be defective
	and it should be returned for replacement.   


	If the drive light came on for a few seconds and went back off,
	the message "Diskette" should be on the display.  If there is
	no text on the screen, adjust the brightness and contrast controls.
	If you still don't see the message, press RESET.  If the screen
	shows is blank, the one of the video connectors probably has
	come loose.  One is located on the video board and the other end
	plugs into the CPU board near the upper right corner as you look
	at the CPU.

	If the message "Diskette" appears, press <BREAK>  The "Cass?"
	prompt should appear.  Press <ENTER> and wait for "Ready".
	Now press <CTRL>; and you should see ^. Pressing <CTRL>- should
	display the underline (_).   This indicates the ROM was installed
	correctly.

27.	Unplug the computer and replace the screw in the back of the cover.
	Then set the machine on its side and install the 10 screws that
	came from the bottom.  Be sure you get them back in the right
	holes.  Tighten but do not force as these bolts are going into
	plastic and can be easily stripped.



